linkTarget.anchoringText: This paper builds on previous work done by Griffin and others (2013). A database consisting of completion and production parameters was assembled from the NDIC and Frac Focus websites and from internal completion documentation. The area of interest for this study was confined to the Central Basin, also known as the “Rough Rider” area, within Townships 148-159N and Ranges 97-105W (Figure 1). The bubbles represent 180-day cumulative oil per foot of completed lateral (180-day cumulative oil/ft), and contours in the background represent water cut.

image-wrap.label: Figure 1
image-wrap.caption: Area of interest in this study was confined to Townships 148-159N and Ranges 97-105W. Middle Bakken wells are shown in red (left) and Three Forks wells are in blue (right). Contours in the background represent stabilized water cut between 90 and 180 producing days.

formatted-caption.caption-text: Area of interest in this study was confined to Townships 148-159N and Ranges 97-105W. Middle Bakken wells are shown in red (left) and Three Forks wells are in blue (right). Contours in the background represent stabilized water cut between 90 and 180 producing days.

figure-specific-caption.caption-text: Middle Bakken wells are shown in red
Three Forks wells are in blue

linkTarget.anchoringText: Figure 4 compares the predicted versus observed 180-day cumulative oil/ft of the BIC and AIC chosen models. The BIC and AIC chosen models are very similar to the multiple regression model 2 in terms of the R-squared and training RMSE results. However, the BIC and AIC chosen models are simpler than the multiple regression model 2 since many of the interaction terms have been eliminated without sizeable reduction of the R-squared value and the training RMSE.

linkTarget.anchoringText: Figure 5 (left) shows the predicted versus observed 180-day cumulative oil/ft for the random forest model. This model gives an R-squared of 0.63 and a training RMSE of 1.538 BO/ft. Figure 6 (left) presents the importance of each of the eight predictors for the Middle Bakken data based on the random forest regression. The importance is measured by permutation of the values of a predictor and measuring the percent decrease in RMSE.

linkTarget.anchoringText: For the Three Forks training set, we performed similar data quality control or preprocessing by examining the histograms, scatterplots, bivariate plots, and coefficient correlations among variables in the database. Figure 8 presents the histogram plots for the Three Forks data. Of the 778 wells in the original Three Forks dataset, there were only 444 wells with non-missing values for the predictors included in the analysis.
